<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageNumber="100">Akenge, [[worker]]; Medje, [[worker]]; Ngayu, [[worker]]; Niangara, [[worker]]; Niapu, [[worker]]. Eightysix specimens, all taken from the stomachs of four species of toads (Bufo polycercus, superciliaris, funereus, and tuberosus) collected by Lang and Chapin.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="101" pageNumber="100">
Stitz has described an 0. intermedius which differs from the typical 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32972" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Odontomachus assiniensis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="assiniensis">assiniensis</taxonomicName>
only in having the striae on the pronotum of the worker more arcuately concentric and therefore more as in O. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:187810" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Odontomachus haematoda (Linnaeus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haematoda">haematoda</taxonomicName>
and not simply transverse. A study of the long series of specimens before me shows that there is great variation in the pronotal striation, many specimens agreeing with Stitz's description; others having the striae in an asymmetrical whorl like that exhibited by the ridges on the tips of the fingers, and in a considerable number the striae are simply transverse, as described by Emery for the typical 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32972" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Odontomachus assiniensis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="assiniensis">assiniensis</taxonomicName>
. I do not regard these differences as more than nest variations and have therefore relegated Stitz's intermedius, which Santschi is willing to regard as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32972" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Odontomachus assiniensis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="assiniensis">assiniensis</taxonomicName>
, to the synonymy.
</paragraph>
